The 3rd Remote Physiological Signal Sensing (RePSS) Challenge & Workshop

To be held at IJCAI 2024, 3rd-9th August 2024, Jeju, Southe Korea 

Overview

The Vision-based Remote Physiological Signal Sensing (RePSS) workshop covers research topics related to remote physiological signal sensing from facial videos. Facial videos contain subtle color and motion change information induced by heartbeats which reveals physiological signals like remote photoplethysmography (rPPG). Extracting subtle physiological signals from facial videos requires robust computer vision algorithms and biomedical signal processing methods. As an interdisciplinary research field, the workshop aims to gather researchers from different disciplines to join thoughts and ideas, and also to provide a platform for fair competition and resource sharing. RePSS workshop is a series starting from the 1st RePSS on CVPR2020, and the 2nd RePSS on ICCV2021, and now the 3rd one. It is organized in the form of “workshop + challenge + invited talks” with an emphasis on the challenge.

Workshop Topics

the workshop will be a complimentary part of the challenge that covers a wider scope, i.e., could be research works related to remote physiological signal sensing from any aspect. The topic includes but is not limited to:

  1. New methodologies developed for remote measurement of all kinds of physiological responses of human bodies, e.g., heart rate, heart rate variability, respiration, blood oxygen saturation, blood pressure, and others.

  2. Hardwires/apparatuses/imaging systems developed for the purpose of remote physiological measurement from the face and body.

  3. New data collected for the purpose of remote physiological measurement.

  4. Solutions for special challenges involved with remote physiological signal sensing, e.g., low-quality video, poor illumination conditions, motions, data with noisy labels or no labels, etc.

  5. Applications of remote physiological sensing, e.g., for medical assessment in hospitals, for health surveillance at home or in other environments, for emotion assessment in various scenarios like for education, job interview, etc., for security and forensics like liveness detection, biometrics, and video editing/synthesis.


Challenge

Challenge tasks are all related to the main theme of remote physiological signal sensing. For the 3rd RePSS, there are two tracks. 

  • Track 1 is self-supervised learning for heart rate measurement using unlabeled facial videos’. Since there are only a few facial videos with HR labels, track 1 mainly focuses on developing self-supervised training methods on unlabeled facial videos. 

  • Track 2 is facial video-based blood pressure measurement, which is an emerging topic and more challenging. Blood pressure measurement requires high-quality physiological signals from facial videos, so participants in this track should design both accurate remote physiological signal measurement algorithm and blood pressure estimation algorithm. 

The challenge will be organized on the Kaggle website, where instructions and data will be shared, and results from participants will be submitted and ranked.
